{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:29:17.551Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Considering Loading States**\n\nI've been examining `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`, noting the existing spin loading indicator, `RefreshCw`. Now, I'm shifting focus to `app/portal/dashboard/page.tsx`. I'm exploring strategies to implement comprehensive handling of loading, error, empty, and offline/fallback states within it. I'm building a design.\n\n\n**Refining Loading Logic**\n\nI'm now implementing state management for `ClientDashboardPage` within `/app/portal/dashboard/page.tsx`. I've established `dashboardData` as `any | null` (initially `null`) and `loading` as a boolean (initially `true`, for now). The strategy involves fetching data, falling back to mock data on error or offline, then setting `loading` to `false`. I'm also planning a subtle, themed loading state with a premium feel, maybe with a shimmer or skeleton. Since `/portal/dashboard` is already wrapped by `ClientPortalLayout`, the shell will persist throughout loading.\n\n\n**Designing the Loading State**\n\nI'm now iterating on the design for the page-level loading state. The shell remains visible, which is great for preserving context. The current design draft looks really nice, with a circular border animation, a centered lightning bolt icon, and an animated, subtle text. It feels much faster and more professional than a full-screen spinner. I'm focusing on the elegant aesthetic of this design.\n\n\n**Refining Error Handling**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on the error state. I envision an inner Zap icon and elegant pulse text: \"ESTABLISHING CRYPTOGRAPHIC LINK...\". It's a premium, professional design that matches the theme. Crucially, I'm thinking about gracefully handling errors.  I'll ensure there's a fallback mechanism, either to static/mock data with a banner, or a dedicated error state.  I like the idea of falling back to offline mock data for API errors or offline scenarios – it maintains a working preview. The existing SECURE DISCLOSURE BANNER is already ideal for these cases.\n\n\n**Implementing Secure Connectivity**\n\nI'm now thinking about the banner design, particularly for the success state, post-data fetch. If the live data loads, I'll switch from the current demo banner to a \"SECURE CONNECTION ESTABLISHED\" banner, using a green theme. The current design in `/app/portal/dashboard/page.tsx` works for fallback situations. I can also replace the existing banner text with \"OFFLINE FALLBACK MODE ACTIVE\" when using mock data.\n\n\n**Finalizing Successful Connection**\n\nI've crafted the secure channel message, displaying the client ID and cryptographically audited logs once live data is fetched successfully. The banner now showcases a green theme, reinforcing a secure connection. I'm satisfied with the comprehensive approach.\n\n\n**Verifying Dependencies**\n\nNow I'm making sure I have all necessary dependencies imported for `/app/portal/dashboard/page.tsx`. I'm confirming the imports, particularly `useState` and `useEffect` from `react`. I'm also double-checking icons like `ShieldCheck` and `RefreshCw`, if they are needed, so I'm bringing them in too.\n\n\n**Reviewing Existing Imports**\n\nI'm now auditing the imported icons within `/app/portal/dashboard/page.tsx` again. I'm noting that `ShieldCheck` is present, alongside many other relevant lucide icons, so I'm well-equipped. I'm now also considering edge cases, specifically, what if dynamic arrays are empty, like projects or tickets? I'll design graceful \"no items\" states, or fallback displays.\n\n\n**Implementing Empty States**\n\nI'm now applying a similar \"no items\" treatment for other dynamic arrays. The \"No Active Sandboxes\" is looking good! I'll apply the same elegant design to other widgets that have dynamic arrays. I'm focusing on consistency in the empty state displays across the dashboard and ensuring a smooth user experience even with no data.\n\n\n**Designing Empty States**\n\nI'm now designing the empty state for the Compliance Documents section within `/app/portal/dashboard/page.tsx`. I'll adapt a similar elegant approach, using a suitable icon and concise message to indicate the absence of documents. The goal is consistent, user-friendly feedback across all dynamic sections.\n\n\n**Designing Invoice Display**\n\nI'm now designing the empty state for Invoices (Financial Ledger). I'll adapt a similar, elegant approach, using a relevant icon and a concise message to indicate the absence of invoices, and consistent user-friendly feedback across all sections. The aim is to mirror the design pattern established with the compliance documents section within `/app/portal/dashboard/page.tsx`, to retain the existing feel.\n\n\n\n**Refining Support Ticket States**\n\nI'm now implementing the \"no tickets\" display within the support wire section of `/app/portal/dashboard/page.tsx`. I'll adapt a similar elegant design, leveraging an appropriate icon and concise message to handle the absence of tickets. The objective is to ensure consistent and user-friendly feedback across all dynamic sections of the dashboard.\n\n\n**Confirming Widget Designs**\n\nI'm now satisfied with the elegant \"no tickets\" display I've implemented in the support wire section. The graceful empty states across all dynamic widgets feels amazing. I'm confirming all designs across the dashboard are high quality.\n\n\n**Defining Design Plan**\n\nI'm now writing out the detailed internal design plan for the client dashboard, starting with the page narrative and visual metaphor, as required, and now refining the design for the Client Dashboard, which acts as the \"Sovereign oversight cockpit\". I'm meticulously defining each element for clarity. I'm focusing on Level III security clearance feel with a real-time connection status banner.\n\n\n**Defining Layout & Interaction**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on the layout and interaction strategies for the Client Dashboard. I'm focusing on the elegant Phase 4 grid, conditional empty states, and a graceful animated loading state. The hover states and interactive toggles need to work as expected. I'm also confirming the mobile strategy, and making sure the bento grid is responsive.\n\n\n\n**Adapting Governance Panel**\n\nI'm now adapting the `GovernancePanel` component to accept an optional `items` prop. I've examined `components/private-app/governance.tsx`, and realized a simple interface change can allow external data injection. This will enable dynamic data population and customization. I'm focusing on ensuring it integrates seamlessly.\n\n\n\n**Updating Compliance Data**\n\nI'm now integrating compliance data into the `GovernancePanel` component. I'm focusing on ensuring data integrity. I've mapped the provided items to `ComplianceRule` objects, setting status based on flags. My code will ensure the display reflects accurate, up-to-date compliance information.\n\n\n"}}
